  "text": "Following the approach used in [CITATION_1] , the goal is to write the given measurement matrix Z as a rank-one perturbation, and make use us recent results from the random matrix theory community on the largest eigenvalue of such rank-one deformation. For convenience, we set the diagonal entries of Z to Z ii = (2p − 1)α, and choose to denote z −1 j by z j since in Z 2 an element is its own inverse. Next, we write the symmetric matrix Z as a random perturbation of a rank-one matrix, with the expected value of its elements given by E(Z ij ) = z i z j pα − z i z j (1 − p)α = z i z j (2p − 1)α. (8.2) Note that the expected value of Z is a rank-one matrix We are now ready to write the matrix Z in the form of a random perturbation of a rank-one matrix Z = E(Z ij ) + R = n(2p − 1)αtt T + R, (8.5) where R is a random matrix with R ii = 0, whose elements R ij = Z ij − E(Z ij ) are zero-mean independent random variables. Using (8.2), the entries of the random matrix R are given by the following mixture model R ij =    z i z j − z i z j (2p − 1)α, (i, j) ∈ E good , with probability pα −z i z j − z i z j (2p − 1)α, (i, j) ∈ E bad , with probability (1 − p)α −z i z j (2p − 1)α, (i, j) ∈ EḠ, with probability 1 − α using the fact that (z i z j ) 2 = 1. Note that in the case of a complete graph, G = K n and α = 1, the variance vanishes when p = 1, since all edges are correct. This is also the case whenever p = 0 and all edges are incorrect, meaning the sign of all equations is flipped, in which case we still recover the original solution. When G is a random graph, the variance is α(1 − α), whenever p = 0 or p = 1.",
